pe":"questionRevisions","id":"108130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108130"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two month history of increasing fatigue, 8 kg weight loss, and increased urination. He also has dull pain in his arms and legs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no pre-existing medical concerns and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks about three glasses of wine a week. He undergoes regular bowel cancer screening. There is no family history of any cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he looks pale. His blood pressure is 125/90mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37\u00b0C. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. Initial investigations reveal that he is hypercalcaemic, with decreased parathyroid hormone and a normocytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be positive?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["BCR-ABL","Calcitonin","Serum Free Light Chains","CA-125","Carcinoembryonic Antigen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is suggestive of multiple myeloma. This diagnosis would account for the patient\u0027s hypercalcaemia manifesting with polyuria and lytic lesions (causing bone pain). His paleness would also be explained by a normocytic anaemia. Biopsy of the bone marrow and urine electrophoresis should be conducted to confirm the diagnosis. An elevation of \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum free light chains\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoembryonic antigen (CEA)\u003C/strong\u003E Is a general cancer marker, raised most commonly in colorectal and pancreatic cancer. These do not typically present with hypercalcaemia and anaemia. CEA may be present in lung cancer, which may secrete ectopic PTH-rP resulting in hypercalcaemia, although this is unlikely given that the patient has no risk factors or respiratory signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcitonin\u003C/strong\u003E is raised in medullary thyroid cancer. This does not typically present with hypercalcaemia or anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBRC-ABL\u003C/strong\u003E (Philadelphia chromosome) is raised most commonly in chronic myeloid leukaemia, and may be raised in other acute leukaemias. This may explain the patient\u0027s symptoms of weight loss, bruising and anaemia, however leukaemias are not typically associated with hypercalcaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECA 125 \u003C/strong\u003Eis strongly associated with ovarian carcinoma - and this patient is a man.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An elevation of serum free light chains is associated with multiple myeloma."],"references":["Chavda SJ, Yong K. Multiple myeloma. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2017;78(2):C21-C27. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28165783/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90542"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"252"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90542","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90542"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-07T08:42:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-07T08:42:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"252"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108130"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":